      <Fragment slot="plain">
        <p class="font-bold text-lg text-navy-900 mb-3">Here's what 1,525 lines boil down to:</p>

        <p class="font-bold text-navy-900 mt-4 mb-2">What is this?</p>
        <p class="mb-3">A complete technical blueprint — a detailed plan for building a system that verifies voters are who they say they are. It's not a law. It's not software you can download. It's a proposal that anyone can read, tear apart, and improve.</p>

        <p class="font-bold text-navy-900 mt-4 mb-2">Why does it exist?</p>
        <p class="mb-3">For 20 years, people across the political spectrum have said "elections are broken" — but nobody has published a concrete, buildable plan to fix any part of it. This tackles one specific piece: verifying that every person who votes is a citizen, is eligible, is alive, and hasn't already voted.</p>

        <p class="mb-3"><strong>VoteChain is a voter <em>verification</em> system — not a voting machine.</strong> It doesn't touch your ballot. It answers four questions with mathematical proof: Are you a citizen? Are you eligible? Are you alive? Have you already voted?</p>

        <p class="font-bold text-navy-900 mt-4 mb-2">"But what about my personal data?"</p>
        <p class="mb-3">VoteChain lives <strong>entirely on the verification side</strong>. It receives a cryptographic "yes, this person checks out" — and that's all it stores. No names. No Social Security numbers. No addresses. No biometrics. Just math that proves someone was verified, without revealing who they are.</p>

        <p class="font-bold text-navy-900 mt-4 mb-2">How it works:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2.5 mb-4">
          <li>Enroll <strong>once</strong> through multi-source identity checks. This generates a <strong>digital credential</strong> — a secure digital key proving you're a verified voter.</li>
          <li>At the polls, the system uses a <strong>zero-knowledge proof</strong> — confirming "yes, this person is eligible" <em>without revealing who they are</em>.</li>
          <li>Every verification event is recorded on an <strong>immutable ledger</strong> — 74 separate computers all have to agree before anything gets written.</li>
          <li>Finalizing any record requires <strong>3 of 4 independent operator groups</strong> to agree — federal, state, auditor, and oversight nodes.</li>
        </ul>

        <p class="font-bold text-navy-900 mt-4 mb-2">How it catches fraud:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2.5 mb-4">
          <li><strong>Instantly at the polls:</strong> Duplicate vote attempts caught in seconds via one-time-use nullifiers.</li>
          <li><strong>In the background:</strong> Death records, court records, and suspicious patterns checked continuously. Target: flagging within 48 hours.</li>
        </ul>

        <p class="font-bold text-navy-900 mt-4 mb-2">The numbers:</p>
        <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2.5 mb-4">
          <li><strong>Cost:</strong> ~$870M to build + ~$375M/year to run (~$5.60 per vote)</li>
          <li><strong>Timeline:</strong> 5-year phased rollout</li>
          <li><strong>Speed:</strong> Under 60 seconds at the polls</li>
        </ul>

        <p class="font-bold text-navy-900 mt-4 mb-2">Who audits?</p>
        <p class="mb-3">Quarterly independent audits. <strong>25 randomly selected citizens</strong> (jury-duty model) choose which firm does the audit. Results are published publicly. The entire system is open source.</p>

        <p class="text-navy-500 text-sm italic mt-4">Close this and read the full blueprint with architecture diagrams, data schemas, and threat models.</p>
